\part{Results for mixtures of ideal gases}\label{part:theory}



\paragraph{Note} The equations used to manipulate different kinds of concentrations
described here are based on a research article that I published in
Portuguese \citep{dias2021revisao}, from which I also reproduce two
tables. Other sources for equations are cited along the text.

\vspace*{12pt}

The equation of state for an ideal gas is
\begin{equation}
pV = nR^{\text{*}}T,\label{eq:tudo}
\end{equation}
where $p$ is pressure, $V$ is the volume occupied by the gas, $n$ is
the number of moles, $R^{\text{*}} = 8{,}31446261815$ $\mathrm{J\,mol^{-1}\,K^{-1}}$
(in SI units) is the universal gas constant, and  $T$ is the
thermodynamic temperature.
% É importante notar que (\ref{eq:tudo}) é um excelente
% modelo para o comportamento dos gases na troposfera.
It can also be written
\begin{equation}
p = n\frac{R^{\text{*}}}{V} T 
       = \frac{m}{M}\frac{R^{\text{*}}}{V} T
= \frac{m}{V}\frac{R^{\text{*}}}{M} T\;\Rightarrow\;
p = \rho R T, \label{eq:prhoRt}
\end{equation}
where $M$ is molar mass and $m$ is the mass of the gas, with
\begin{equation}
m = nM. \label{eq:mnM}
\end{equation}
The gas constant and density are
\begin{align}
R &= \frac{R^{\text{*}}}{M},\label{eq:RRM}\\
\rho &= \frac{m}{V}. \label{eq:def-rho}
\end{align}



Equations (\ref{eq:tudo})--(\ref{eq:def-rho}) also apply to a
\emph{mixture} of ideal gases with a few modifications.  Let $i$ be
each gas in the mixture; the total number of moles is
\begin{equation}
n = \sum_{i} n_i,\label{eq:total-n}
\end{equation}
where $n_i$ is the number of moles of gas $i$.  Assume that the gas
law applies for each gas; in the partial pressure model, each gas
exerts a partial pressure $p_i$, and all gases share a common volume $V$:
\begin{equation}
p_i V = n_i R^{\text{*}}T.\label{eq:gas-pi}
\end{equation}
The total pressure is
\begin{equation}
p = \sum_{i} p_{i}.\label{eq:sum-p-i}
\end{equation}
Summing over (\ref{eq:gas-pi}) recovers the gas law for the mixture:
\begin{align*}
  \sum_{i} \left( p_i V \right) &= \sum_i \left(n_i R^{\text{*}}T\right),\\
  \left(\sum_{i} p_i  \right)V &= \left( \sum_i  n_i\right)R^{\text{*}}T,\\
  p V &= nR^{\text{*}}T.
\end{align*}
By the same token, in the partial volume model each gas occupies a
volume $V_i$ under the same pressure $p$:
\begin{equation}
p V_i = n_i R^{\text{*}}T,\label{eq:gas-Vi}
\end{equation}
with
\begin{equation}
V = \sum_{i}V_i.\label{eq:sum-V-i}
\end{equation}
and again summing over (\ref{eq:gas-Vi}) recovers the gas law for the mixture:
\begin{align*}
  \sum_{i} \left( p V_i \right) &= \sum_i \left(n_i R^{\text{*}}T\right),\\
  p\left(\sum_{i}  V_i\right) &= \left( \sum_i  n_i\right)R^{\text{*}}T,\\
  p V &= nR^{\text{*}}T.
\end{align*}


Taking the ratio of (\ref{eq:gas-pi}) to (\ref{eq:tudo}) and of
(\ref{eq:gas-Vi}) to (\ref{eq:tudo}), the partial pressure fraction,
the partial volume fraction, and the molar fraction are all given by
\begin{equation}
x_i = \frac{p_i}{p} = \frac{V_i}{V} =  \frac{n_i}{n}.\label{eq:fracoes-gas}
\end{equation}


The state equation for each gas can also be written
\begin{equation}
p_i = n_i\frac{R^{\text{*}}}{V} T 
       = \frac{m_i}{M_i}\frac{R^{\text{*}}}{V} T
       = \frac{m_i}{V}\frac{R^{\text{*}}}{M_i} T\;\Rightarrow\;
p_i = \rho_i R_i T,\label{eq:prhoRt-chi}
\end{equation}
in analogy with (\ref{eq:prhoRt}). The molar mass of gas $i$ is $M_i$
and its mass is $m_i$, with
\begin{equation}
m_i = n_i M_i. \label{eq:mnMi}
\end{equation}
The gas constant and density of gas $i$ are
\begin{align}
  R_i &= \frac{R^{\text{*}}}{M_i} \label{eq:Rchidef}, \\
  \rho_i &= \frac{m_i}{V}.\label{eq:def-rho-chi}
\end{align}


Equation (\ref{eq:prhoRt-chi}) allows to obtain $R$ in
(\ref{eq:prhoRt}) in terms of the $R_i$\is\ as follows. The total mass
is
\begin{equation}
  m = \sum_{i} m_i;\label{eq:mass-total}
\end{equation}
the gas densities also sum up:
\begin{equation}
\rho = \frac{m}{V} = \frac{\sum_i m_i}{V} = \sum_i \frac{m_i}{V} =
\sum_i \rho_i.\label{eq:rho-total}
\end{equation}
This leads to the definition of the \emph{mass fraction}, 
\begin{equation}
c_i \equiv \frac{m_i}{m}=\frac{\rho_i}{\rho}.\label{eq:def-c-chi}
\end{equation}
Summing (\ref{eq:prhoRt-chi}) over all components,
\begin{align}
  \sum_{i} p_i &= \sum_{i} \rho_i R_i T,\nonumber \\
  p &= \left( \sum_{i} \rho_i R_i \right)T \equiv \rho R T. \label{eq:def-R-mix}
\end{align}
Note that (\ref{eq:def-R-mix}) \emph{defines} the gas constant of the
mixture. Proceeding, 
\begin{align}
  R &= \frac{\sum_{i} \rho_i R_i}{\rho}\nonumber \\
  &= \frac{\sum_{i} \frac{m_i}{V}R_i}{\frac{m}{V}}\nonumber\\
  &= \sum_{i} \frac{m_i}{m} R_i = \sum_{i} c_i R_i. \label{eq:cchi-Rrchi}
\end{align}

By the same token, the \emph{mean molar mass} is
\begin{equation}
  M = \sum_{i} x_i M_i = \frac{\sum_i n_i M_i}{n} = \frac{m}{n}.\label{eq:mnMagain}
\end{equation}
Note how (\ref{eq:mnMagain}) recovers (\ref{eq:mnM}) explicitly for
the mixture.  Finally, $R$ for the mixture can be obtained from (\ref{eq:cchi-Rrchi}):
\begin{align}
  R &= \frac{1}{m} \left( \sum_i m_i R_i\right)  \nonumber \\
    &= \frac{1}{m} \left( \sum_i n_i M_i R_i\right)  \nonumber \\
    &= \frac{1}{m} \left( \sum_i n_i R^{\text{*}}\right) = \frac{1}{m}
  \left( \sum_i n_i\right) R^{\text{*}} \nonumber \\
    &= \frac{n}{m} R^{\text{*}}  = \frac{R^{\text{*}}}{M}{\,}, \label{eq:Rmixagain}
\end{align}
Equation (\ref{eq:Rmixagain}) is the same as (\ref{eq:RRM}), but now
obtained explicitly for the mixture.

The atmosphere is often modeled in a simplified way as a mixture of 2
gases: the main varying component, water vapor, and ``dry air''. The dry
air component is equivalent to the mixture of all other
components. Two variables needed for the calculations involving moist
air (water vapor and dry air) are the dry air mean molar mass $M_d$
and the dry air gas constant $R_d$. They can be obtained from
published gas concentrations in a standard atmosphere.



Table \ref{tab:ppgas} shows several sources of concentrations of gases
in a dry atmosphere. The standard atmosphere is defined in 
\cite{coesa1976standard}; The 1\rst\ edition of
\cite{iribarne.godson--atmospheric} predates it a little bit, while a
relatively recent reference of dry atmosphere components is 
\cite{wallace2006atmospheric}.
Non-academic references are 
\cite{wikipedia--atmosphere-of-earth} and \cite{co2--earth}; the
latter reports a molar fraction of 414{.}11 for 
CO\sub{2} in 2020/03/05.


To ensure consistency, all molar mass values were obtained in
\cite{nist2020search}. In table \ref{tab:ppgas}, the CO\sub{2}
concentration increases in time.  However, for several constituents
the concentrations do not change (por example, for Argon in COE, WAL e
WIK): it appears that these concentrations have been reproduced in the
several references without more recent measurements. Because of this,
the concentrations do not always sum up to 1. In the absence of
comprehensive and recent measurements, we made small adjustments to
the components' concentrations heuristically to eforce that they sum
to 1 in the adopted values, in the last column.







