Because different sources use slightly different values of molar
masses and the universal gas constant, there are small differences
between their reported values and a recalculation using the most
recent values reported in \cite{nist2020search}. I calculated $R_d$
using pressure and temperature of a standard atmosphere at sea level,
$p = 101\,325\,\mathrm{Pa}$ e $T = 288.15\,\mathrm{K}$
\citep{coesa1976standard}. Instead of $M$ and $R$ for a generic
mixture, I now use $M_d$ and $R_d$, which are calculated as follows:
(\ref{eq:fracoes-gas}) is used to calculate $p_i$; para o cálculo da
pressăo parcial $p_i$; (\ref{eq:Rchidef}) for the gas constants $R_i$;
(\ref{eq:prhoRt-chi}) for the densities $\rho_i$; (\ref{eq:mnMagain})
to obtain $M_d$ e (\ref{eq:cchi-Rrchi}) to obtain $R_d$. Results are
shown in table \ref{tab:msrs}.

In \texttt{atmgas}, the molar masses adopted are from column $M_i$ of
table \ref{tab:ppgas}, and $M_d$ and $R_d$ are from line ADV of table
\ref{tab:msrs}. 

\part{Constants and procedures}

\section{Constants}

Gas names are used to index associative arrays. The valid gas names
are \texttt{"DRY", "N2", "O2", "AR", "H2O", "CO2", "NE", "HE", "KR",
  "XE", "CH4", "H2", "O3", "N2O"} and correspond to those in table
\ref{tab:ppgas}, except for water vapor (\texttt{"H2O"}). The
following associative arrays are defined:
\begin{mydescription}{2cm}
  \item[\texttt{Mmol}] The molar masses in $\mathrm{kg\,mol^{-1}}$.
  \item[\texttt{Rgas}] The gas constants $R_i$ in $\mathrm{J\,kg^{-1}\,K^{-1}}$.
\end{mydescription}
For example,
\begin{lstlisting}[style=lstsimple]
Mmol["N2"] = 2.80134000e-02
Rgas["N2"] = 2.96803052e+02
\end{lstlisting}

In adition, \texttt{Ru} is the universal gas constant, and
\texttt{Rd}, \texttt{Rv}, \texttt{Rc} are defined as useful aliases
for \texttt{Rgas["DRY"]}, \texttt{Rgas["H2O"]}, \texttt{Rgas["CO2"]}.

